WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.780
You wanted to see the real thing, so here it is — no graphical interface, just the actual script.

2
00:00:07.080 --> 00:00:12.826
There's the listing: the PowerShell file, the one-click macro, and nothing else.

3
00:00:13.126 --> 00:00:25.504
And look at what the script itself says it does: it attaches to your already-open Outlook and reads the study folder — it never moves, deletes, or modifies your mail; it only reads.

4
00:00:25.804 --> 00:00:38.284
The one function worth seeing is the sanitizer: before any email is saved, it strips out scripts, styles, and tracking — so a note can never run code or phone home when you open it.

5
00:00:39.284 --> 00:00:42.792
Now let me run it on a real folder, on this machine.

6
00:00:43.092 --> 00:00:46.491
Here's the knowledge base folder, with its drop inbox.

7
00:00:46.791 --> 00:00:57.866
The ad-hoc capture — the one you already have — is exactly this: you drop a few study emails into that inbox, which is what the one-click Outlook macro does for you.

8
00:00:58.166 --> 00:01:01.361
Three operational emails, ready to file.

9
00:01:02.361 --> 00:01:03.361
Run the script.

10
00:01:03.661 --> 00:01:09.034
Each email becomes one read-only, structured note, written to the Notes folder.

11
00:01:09.334 --> 00:01:14.676
And every one is stamped with its Outlook EntryID, recorded in seen-dot-json.

12
00:01:14.976 --> 00:01:21.660
That watermark is what makes it safe to run unattended — it is how the script knows what it has already filed.

13
00:01:22.660 --> 00:01:30.378
Here is one of the filed notes — subject, sender, the time it was captured, and the operations-only footer.

14
00:01:30.678 --> 00:01:33.072
Now the safety net, made visible.

15
00:01:33.372 --> 00:01:37.016
The source email carried a tracking script and a remote pixel.

16
00:01:37.316 --> 00:01:45.082
The filed note has neither: the script is gone, and the remote image is neutralized — turned into a dead, blocked link.

17
00:01:45.382 --> 00:01:47.834
Every note is sanitized on the way in.

18
00:01:48.834 --> 00:01:50.705
And the watermark earns its keep.

19
00:01:51.005 --> 00:01:56.603
Drop the very same emails in again, run the script again — and it skips every one.

20
00:01:56.903 --> 00:01:59.163
Zero filed, three skipped.

21
00:01:59.463 --> 00:02:06.339
It is genuinely idempotent: it never files the same message twice, no matter how often it runs.

22
00:02:07.339 --> 00:02:15.168
Finally, the ad-hoc one-click — a small Outlook macro, for the rare email that lives outside your study folder.

23
00:02:15.468 --> 00:02:23.686
So that is the whole tool: one Outlook rule to route the mail, one scheduled script to file it, real notes on a real drive.

24
00:02:23.986 --> 00:02:30.153
No graphical interface, operations-only — and the validated systems still own every number.
